        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In order to capture high velocity 86 GHz SiO (v=1, J=2-1) masers with width of order 3 km/s, we place four dual-polarization spectral windows in one sideband spanning -7500 to +4900 km/s with 1.7 km/s (488 kHz) channels after Hanning smoothing (a circular orbit at 1 millipc from the central black hole will have velocity 4160 km/s).  Some maser lines will be only marginally resolved, but this should be adequate for detection.  The data rate cannot be lowered (see below).  We center one spectral window on the rest frame of the SiO maser, one redshifted by 930 MHz (overlapping by 7 MHz), and two blueshifted by equal amounts.  We opt for an extra blueshifted band because high velocity masers approaching the observer can get a relativistic beaming boost when approaching (and a corresponding dimming when receding).  This effect will be at most of order 5--10%.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>While the requested 0.5 arcsec synthesized beam --- spanning the inner 10 millipc at the Galactic Center --- will not allow for immediate spatial localization of all detected masers, it will provide instantaneous radial velocities and positions for stars outside of the inner ~20 mpc.  If any masers are detected within the central 10 mpc, they can be subsequently localized with the complete ALMA array at its highest planned resolution to less than the 2.0 millipc (0.05") synthesized beam at 86 GHz (0.2 mpc = 40 AU = 0.005", which only requires a S/N of ~5 to centroid; trivial for our survey detection threshold of 10 mJy).  The primary beam will span the inner 1.4 pc (72" FWHM), so we will re-detect the known and newly discovered SiO masers, which will be useful for calibration, verification, and astrometry.  Since this is a detection observation and the masers are point-like (they become resolved at less than ~0.001" at the GC distance) the uv coverage of the Cycle 3 array is not a concern.

This program needs no special scheduling, weather, calibration accuracy, or imaging fidelity.  </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>According to the ALMA sensitivity calculator, for 488 kHz (1.7 km/s) channels obtained in two polarizations, 36 antennas, and the default water vapor column (5.2 mm, or T_sys = 78 K), we can reach 2 mJy rms noise per beam per channel in 34 minutes of on-source integration.  Typical 86 GHz SiO masers already detected near the GC are at least 100 mJy, so a 5 sigma detection threshold of 10 mJy represents an order of magnitude improvement.   This sensitivity is needed to enable the detection of weak masers in stars that may have undergone some atmospheric stripping and to be certain that we detect any star that might be used for tests of general relativity.  The short integration time will provide ample opportunity for new discoveries; additional time will not substantially improve the science.  The total time request including overheads is 1.03 hours.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The data rate is high, 24 Mb/s, but is required to conduct the wide spectral search of velocity space while maintaining the narrow channel widths appropriate for SiO masers.  Maser lines will be marginally resolved.  The total integration time requested is short, so the total data volume will not be too large (88 GB).
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
